  <h2>Saskatchewan Garden Timing Notes</h2>

  <p>
    Saskatchewan has a classic prairie climate: long, cold winters, a rapid spring warm-up,
    strong mid-summer heat, and meaningful early fall frost risk. The season can be productive —
    but it rarely forgives late starts or overly long-maturity crops.
  </p>

  <h3>1) Spring moves fast — but frost risk lingers</h3>
  <p>
    Once snow melts, temperatures can rise quickly. However, late spring frost events are common,
    especially outside major urban heat pockets. Planting by calendar date alone often leads to setbacks.
  </p>
  <p class="small muted">
    If you’ve ever wondered why the “average last frost” didn’t match reality,
    <a href="/guides/average-frost-date-vs-actual-weather/">
      this explains how actual weather differs from averages
    </a>.
  </p>

  <h3>2) Mid-summer heat is strong and decisive</h3>
  <p>
    June and July often build growing degree days rapidly across southern Saskatchewan.
    This is when warm-season crops do most of their development.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Short-to-mid season varieties are safest.</strong></li>
    <li><strong>Late planting of long-season crops is risky.</strong></li>
    <li><strong>Early transplanting (with protection if needed) improves odds.</strong></li>
  </ul>

  <h3>3) Fall cooling can arrive quickly</h3>
  <p>
    September frost is common in many regions. Once overnight temperatures trend downward,
    heat-loving crops slow dramatically and may not finish.
  </p>
  <p class="small muted">
    If you're unsure whether peppers will realistically finish,
    <a href="/guides/will-peppers-mature-before-first-frost-in-a-short-season/">
      this guide walks through how to estimate maturity before frost
    </a>.
  </p>

  <h3>4) Wind exposure affects performance</h3>
  <p>
    Open prairie winds increase moisture loss and stress young plants.
    Sheltered gardens often outperform exposed sites even when frost dates are identical.
  </p>
  <p class="small muted">
    If your yard behaves differently than regional data suggests,
    <a href="/guides/why-your-backyard-may-be-warmer-or-colder-than-your-zip-code/">
      this explains why backyard microclimates vary
    </a>.
  </p>

  <h3>How to use your numbers</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>Use frost timing to define your outer planting boundaries.</li>
    <li>Match crop maturity to realistic seasonal heat.</li>
    <li>Add margin if you're in a frost-prone low spot or exposed prairie site.</li>
  </ol>

  <p class="small muted" style="margin:0.5rem 0 0 0;">
    In Saskatchewan, conservative variety choice and early planning
    usually outperform pushing the season’s limits.
  </p>
</section>